":"5 april 1590","Arlesey, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Arlesey, Bedfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Tamworth, Staffordshire, Inglaterra":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Of,Wherwell,Hampshire,England":"Wherwell, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Of, Brown Candover, Hamps, Eng":"Brown Candover, Hampshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1486–":"1486–Deceased","1480–1543":"1480–1543","1480–1556":"1480–1556","1500–Male":"1500–Deceased","1501–1555":"1501–1555","1503–1555":"1503–1555","1504–1598":"1504–1598","1486–Female":"1486–Deceased","1 Jun 1501":"1 June 1501","1480":"1480","1503":"1503","1558":"1558","1501":"1501","1556":"1556","1500":"1500","1555":"1555","1587":"1587","1598":"1598","1543":"1543","1486":"1486","1585":"1585","1549":"1549","1504":"1504","16 DEC 1537":"16 December 1537","05 Apr 1590":"5 April 1590","Arlesey, Central Bedfordshire Unitary Authority, Bedfordshire, England":"Arlesey, Bedfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Tamworth, Staffordshire, Inglaterra":"Tamworth, Staffordshire, England","Staffordshire, England":"Staffordshire, England","Of,Wherwell,Hampshire,England":"Wherwell, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","Of, Brown Candover, Hamps, Eng":"Brown Candover, Hampshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hill","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: topographic name for someone who lived on or by a hill, from Middle English <i>hill</i>, <i>hell</i>, <i>hull</i> ‘hill’ (Old English <i>hyll</i>). Compare   Hiller  . This surname is also very common among African Americans.","English: possibly in some cases from the personal name <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of some name such as   Hilger   or   Hillary  .","German: from a short form of   Hildebrand   or any of a variety of other names, male and female, containing ancient Germanic <i>hild</i> ‘battle’ as the first element."],"variants":[{"name":"Hillock","meanings":["English and Scottish: topographic name for someone who lived ‘(by the) small hill’, from Middle English <i>hillok</i>, a diminutive of <i>hille</i> (Old English <i>hyll</i> ‘hill’). See   Hill  ."]},{"name":"Hills","meanings":["English: variant of   Hill   with genitival <i>-s</i> if a relationship name, attested in Matilda <i>Hilles</i>, 1327 (Somerset), where the genitival form may signify widowhood; or with plural <i>-s</i> if habitational, attested in Johanne <i>de Hyles</i>, 1379 (Bickerstaffe, Lancashire), and Ricardo <i>del Hyles</i>, 1379 (Great Eccleston, Lancashire); or, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, probably the most common form."]},{"name":"Hiller","meanings":["German: metronymic from <i>Hille</i>, a pet form of the female personal name <i>Hildegund</i> (see   Hilke  ).","German: from a masculine personal beginning with the ancient Germanic element <i>hild</i> ‘strife, battle’.","German: variant of <b>Hüller</b> (see   Huller  )."]},{"name":"Hil","meanings":["Altered form of English   Hill  .","Dutch (<b>Van den Hil</b>): topographic name from <i>hil, hul</i> ‘hill’, particularly in the sense of a <i>flight hill</i> above sea level in the southwestern Netherlands."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":63,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705202,"age":72,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705207,"age":99,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705208,"age":101,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - 